rbyshire, England","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"about 1175–1207":"about 1175–1207","1175–1207":"1175–1207","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1203–Male":"1203–Deceased","1205–Male":"1205–Deceased","1206–1248":"1206–1248","1132–1197":"1132–1197","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","1132":"1132","1197":"1197","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","before 1206":"before 1206","1180":"1180","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1203":"1203","about 1205":"about 1205","before 1174":"before 1174","about 1203":"about 1203","about 1187":"about 1187","about 1175":"about 1175","about 1197":"about 1197","1207":"1207","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Longford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Langford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Langford","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called with Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, such as Langford (Bedfordshire, Nottinghamshire, Essex, Norfolk)."]}]},{"name":"Oliver","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French name, <i>Olivier</i>, recorded as the name of one of Charlemagne's paladins (retainers), the close companion in arms of Roland in the Chanson de Roland. Whereas Roland is headstrong and rash, Oliver is thoughtful and cautious. Ostensibly this name derives from Late Latin <i>olivarius</i> ‘olive tree’ (  compare  Olive  ), but Charlemagne's other paladins all bear solidly Germanic names, so it is more probably an altered form of a Germanic name, perhaps distantly connected with Old Norse <i>Óleifr</i> ‘ancestral relic’. It has remained in more or less continuous use since the medieval period, becoming ever more popular since the 1980s."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Oliver de Longford was born about 1175, in Longford, Derbyshire, England, his father, Nigel de Longford, was 45 and his mother, Margaret FitzHubert, was 37. He married Avice de Goosnargh about 1187. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1207, at the age of 33."},"et":{"about 1175–1207":"umbes 1175–1207","1175–1207":"1175–1207","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1203–Male":"1203–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1206–1248":"1206–1248","1132–1197":"1132–1197","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1132":"1132","1197":"1197","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","before 1206":"enne 1206","1180":"1180","1206":"1206","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1203":"1203","about 1205":"umbes 1205","before 1174":"enne 1174","about 1203":"umbes 1203","about 1187":"umbes 1187","about 1175":"umbes 1175","about 1197":"umbes 1197","1207":"1207","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1175–1207":"noin 1175–1207","1175–1207":"1175–1207","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1203–Male":"1203–Kuollut","1205–Male":"1205–Kuollut","1206–1248":"1206–1248","1132–1197":"1132–1197","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","1132":"1132","1197":"1197","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","before 1206":"ennen vuotta 1206","11